Using Rembrandt

This Rmarkdown document will illustrate some of the features of the REMBRANDT R package.

Rembrandt can be installed using the following code:

library(devtools)
install_github("MilesLab/Rembrandt")

After Rembrandt is installed, we can load in the packages as below.

library(Rembrandt)

Rembrant includes several files in the package. We can identify them as below.

list.files(system.file("extdata", package = "Rembrandt"))
## [1] "COVID_seqs.fa"             "covid.saf"                
## [3] "patient_barcode_table.csv" "simulation_actual.csv"    
## [5] "test_data_1.fq"            "test_data_2.fq"           
## [7] "test.forward.barcodes.csv" "test.reverse.barcodes.csv"

A description of the important files will be as follows.

The COVID_seqs.fa amplicon sequences file

The COVID_seqs.fa is a fasta file that contains the amplicon sequences. From here we can build an index to perform alignments.

We can obtain the path of the file as follows.

covid_seqs_path = system.file("extdata","COVID_seqs.fa", package = "Rembrandt")

Using cat in command line, we can visualize these files.

cat COVID_seqs.fa
## >N1_SARS_COV2
## GACCCCAAAATCAGCGAAATGCACCCCGCATTACGTTTGGTGGACCCTCAGATTCAACTGGCAGTAACCAGAATGGAGAA
CGC
## >RNAseP
## GATTTGGACCTGCGAGCGGGTTCTGACCTGAAGGCTCTGCGCGGACTTGTGGAGACAGCCGCTC

The covid.saf annotation file

The covid.saf is a simplified annotation file that will be used for determining feature counts. It essentially is the amplicons and their coordinates.

The path of the file is as below.

covid_saf_path = system.file("extdata","covid.saf", package = "Rembrandt")

The file contents are shown as below.

read.table(covid_saf_path,header = T)
##         GeneID          Chr Start End Strand
## 1 N1_SARS_COV2 N1_SARS_COV2     1  83      +
## 2       RNAseP       RNAseP     1  64      +

The test data

We have included files as a test dataset. This will be run as an example.

The fastq files test_data_1.fq and test_data_2.fq are the paired-end test files. Rembrandt requires paired end files.

We can import the paths of these files as follows.

test_data_1_path = system.file("extdata","test_data_1.fq", package = "Rembrandt")
test_data_2_path = system.file("extdata","test_data_2.fq", package = "Rembrandt")

The files each contain 2336 reads each which makes them readily available for a quick test analysis.
The next set of files are the test barcodes files. They contain the list of barcodes.

This is the test.forward.barcodes.csv and the test.reverse.barcodes.csv.

These are the list of barcodes for the test data.

Processing the reads

We are now ready to start processing of the reads.

The first step is to create a temporary directory for this vignette purposes.

dir.create("temp_vignette")
list.files("temp_vignette")
## character(0)

The first step will be to de-multiplex the reads by the forward or plate barcodes.nreads is the number of reads that will be iterated through by the yield() functions from the ShortRead package.

summary.plate.split = split_plate_barcodes(pair1_filepath = test_data_1_path, 
                                           pair2_filepath = test_data_2_path,nreads = 100,
                                           forward_barcode = test.forward.barcodes, 
                                           output_prefix = "temp_vignette/plate_demultiplexed")

The newly split files are as below.

A for-loop is run over each of these resulting files for the reverse or well-specific split. The newly created files are as follows.

summary.well.split.list = list()
for(i in 1:length(plate_demultiplexed_files1)){
output.prefix = gsub(x = plate_demultiplexed_files1[i], pattern = "_1.fq", replacement = "")
output.prefix = paste(output.prefix, "_well_demultiplexed", sep = "")
summary.well.split.list[[i]] = split_well_barcodes(pair1_filepath = plate_demultiplexed_files1[i], 
                                           pair2_filepath = plate_demultiplexed_files2[i],
                                           nreads = 100,
                                           reverse_barcode = test.reverse.barcodes, 
                                           output_prefix = output.prefix)
}

Aligning the reads

The next step is to align the resulting fastq files to the amplicon sequences. This will be done using the Rsubread package.

We can build an index for the COVID amplicons as below using the covid_seqs_path path for the fasta file.

dir.create("temp_vignette/alignment_index")
Rsubread::buildindex('temp_vignette/alignment_index/COVID_amplicon_index',reference = covid_seqs_path)

dir.create("temp_vignette/alignment_results")
output_bam_files = c()

for(i in 1:length(final_to_align_1)){
  output.file = gsub(x = final_to_align_1[i], pattern = "_1.fq", replacement = "")
  output.file = gsub(x = output.file, pattern = "temp_vignette/", replacement = "")
  output.file = paste("temp_vignette/alignment_results/",
                      output.file, "_aligned.bam", sep = "")
  output_bam_files[i] = output.file
  
}

Rsubread::align(index = "temp_vignette/alignment_index/COVID_amplicon_index",
                readfile1 = final_to_align_1,
                readfile2 = final_to_align_2,
                output_file = output_bam_files,
                input_format = "FASTQ")

We can store the counts information into the following matrix.

fc.counts = fc.alignments$counts
fc.samples = colnames(fc.counts)

patient.index = c()
for(i in 1:nrow(patient_barcode_table)){
  patient.index[i] = intersect(grep(pattern = as.character(patient_barcode_table$plate_barcode[i]),
                x = fc.samples),
            grep(pattern = as.character(patient_barcode_table$well_barcode[i]),
                 x = fc.samples))
  fc.samples[patient.index[i]] = as.character(patient_barcode_table$patient_id[i])
}
